content.description:
Just above the top of the fixed approach rope is a small face with three cracks. Start under the rightmost crack and traverse to the far left left and up leftmost one. Climb the crack till it fades. A tricky face move leads to the anchor

Far left upper left of the area above raging duck and pink flamingo.
Single rack.

First part is a scramble to a set of chains. Continue up to the dyke and face climb through four bolts to the top chains.

In the clean starts area
Four bolts, gear to 2", chains at the top.

Start at the bolt to the left of stumps, follow the horinzontal and diagonal cracks trending left to the arete. Finish up a finger crack by the tree.

Second walks off.



To the left of Stumps on the upper ledge, start at the bolt. Trend left.

Bolts, gear, extra from purple camalot and smaller.

Start up the wide dyke of Pink Flamingo and then step left when possible into the crack along the left side of the face. Follow this crack up to the ledge. 
  
 A easier link-up that avoids the crux of "Barefoot in China Town" and provides an enjoyable route to the cat crack ledge.

Face under Cat Crack in the lower left side of area.
Set of nuts and cams to 3". Dodgy .3 c4 placement on the dyke.

Start up the crack left of Pink Flamingo with a tricky low move, then jig left.

Face under Cat Crack in the lower left side of area. Crack to the left of pink flamingo.
Set of nuts and cams to 3"

Im not sure if this already has a name but i encountered a bat in there when i first did it so here goes the batcave.

Start in layback flake and when you can, enter behind the flake to exit into cornflakes. Follow cornflakes to the top.

I dont think bringing a rope here won't do you any good cause it would probably get stuck behind the flakes. So not quite a safe climb but if you're confident in your climbing its a really fun little variation.


none?

climbs.name: Bruce Lee Vs. The Kiss Army

content.description:
Start between Neat and Cool and the offwidth to the left and make thin face moves over the bulge and directly up to the break. Place some gear in the break then move straight up on obvious holds and balance up into the scoop above. Bouldery moves gain the sloping arete and a weird mantle leads to easier ground above. Cryptic and exciting!

A couple hand size peices in the horizontal, there are tonnes of bomber placements to choose from.

A great hand crack. Plenty of protection for new leaders. Popular. Just to the right (squeezed) is a bolted face climb. Maybe .10b? At the left end of Neat and Cool, there is a large ledge above Pink Flamingo, 5.10b and Raging Duck. Cat Crack starts up here. This crack is left of the big flake/arete forming The Edge. To get to it, you need to mantle up onto a boulder (awkward with another boulder above it). Then climb the corner to the ledge. Many do this unroped, but you can also belay this. There is a two-bolt rappel anchor on the ledge (top of Pink Flamingo). Gear to 2 or 2.5 inches. There are placements for larger gear, but there are also small placements right next to those. Two bolts at the top. Walk off right to get to the main trail, left to get to the big ledge system.

Just above the top of the fixed approach rope is a small face with three cracks. Start  under the rightmost crack and traverse left and up the middle one.

Far left upper left of the area above raging duck and pink flamingo.
set of nuts and cams from .6-2"

Fun finger cracks lead up a corner to a nice ledge.  The crack to the left is 5.8-.

Far right side of Neat and Cool 75 ft past the blasted wall.
Gear to 1.5"

Follow the finger crack right beside the tree into the dirt groove, passing the tree in the groove and finishing on the crack on the right of the groove. 



Immediately left of the second dirt groove on the ledge.

Standard rack.

The right-facing corner, left of Flying Circus.  Mostly hands.

Gear to 3.5 inches.  2-bolt anchor with chains at the top.  Rappel, or walk off straight back (slightly left) from the top of the route.

Climb up the jumble of blocks and flakes to the right of the really large flake (Lieback Flake, 5.9) and the obvious corner offwidth crack (Neat and Cool Offwidth).  Gear placement is tricker than it looks.
content.protection: Single rack to #3.  Two bolt anchor at the top.  You can also walk off.

content.description:
Climb onto the large block between Mouse Trap and Corner Crack. Once on top, face climb past three bolts to the left of the arete. Avoid any temptation to use the Mouse Trap crack. Finish up using either the two cracks above. The first bolt of off the large block is somewhat high and unprotected if you start up using Corner Crack. If you instead use Mouse Trap to start, you can place a high piece of gear in the crack and then step over to the block or alternatively face climb over to the first bolt from the crack. Standard Rack, 3 bolts

Two anchors at the top, one with rap rings and one without.

The crux of this climb starts after you clip the last bolt.

Same as the beginning of Flying circus, go up the crack then climb on good feet  (R) to first bolt. Rap from anchors on top.
a few nuts and some med. size cams, after the last bolt there is a gear placement at the exit move's--- gray ? red alien.

This is a sustained fingercrack and a great climb. Its often toproped but I found it to be a fine lead. Its rock is rather polished from TR traffic.

Its on the main wall of neat and cool left of the overhang and right of the dihedral the crack looks awesome splitting the face.
Nuts, smaller cams.. you'll figure it out.

climbs.name: Geritol
climbs.fa: Don Serl, Jim Campbell, Dave Harris

content.description:
a nice climb up cracks to a hard face more that's protected with bolts.

right side of N&C middle of the face with the horizontal crack.
small cams/draws

climbs.name: Gross Incompetence
climbs.fa: Robin Barley, Chris Murrell, Howie Richardson 1981

content.description:
Start up the opening cracks of Geritol. Keep moving up and left to hit the traverse ledge at the arete. Go around the corner and make an awkward step down into Neat & Cool just above the crux overlap of that route. Continue up Neat and Cool to the top.

Pretty obvious but seldom climbed because of the way it traverses through parts of three other routes, avoiding the cruxes of all of them. Descend as per Neat & Cool.
Trad rack to 3", mostly finger to hand size. Bring a few longer slings or (as on the FA) use double ropes to manage rope drag.

The crux comes reaching the first bolt and getting established on the upper wall. There is a bit of ledge if you fall but at least you get a couple bolts. Follow Gross Incompetence until the ledge then trend right following the bolt line. Tricky face climbing on edges and crystals. Finishes with some lay backing on a mini arete feature.

Starts off the right hand corner of the giant block right of Neat and Cool. There is a gap you step over and then swing into leftward cracks that traverse the wall. You can also start off the ground further right where there is a little block and a more vertical crack.
Trad gear to the little ledge then two bolts to a bolted anchor with rap rings. Mostly tips to finger size cams with a couple thin hand and hand size pieces up to BD #1.

Climb up the slabby face just to the right of TreeBeard past a low bolt, to faults and a high bolt.

On the ledge above above pink flamingo, just to the right of TreeBeard and a couple meters left of cat crack.
2 bolts and cams from .6-2"

This is a short route with perhaps twenty feet of 5.11a climbing right off the deck followed by another ten feet of 5.8.  Despite that, the climbing is good and worthwhile.  The crux is sutained finger-tips with tough laybacking and stemming. 
  
 This route is often cited as a good first 5.11 gear lead.  I think that it is, as long as the leader does place adequate protection (since it's tough right off the deck).

This is the right-facing dihedral immediately right of the drill holes from where the cliff was blasted.

Small finger-tip-sized Stoppers and a small cam or two for the crux. A few medium Stoppers to finish. Bolted anchor with chains can be found near the top of the cliff.

Thin fingers and feet up, minimal rests, small gear To the right of There you go Andy is a thin continuous seam up to the top Gear - fingers at most

Hangars at top

The left side of the obvious flake right of the Flying Circus. A heady route with limited pro- climb the flake to the top, clip a bolt, then climb straight up to the top.

Gear (not much, a cam and a couple of nuts will do)

The obvious off-width to the far right of Pink Flamingo. Named after one of the the FA's favorite off-width in the creek, "The Big baby"

The far left and lower face of Neat and Cool wall, to the far right of Pink Flamingo
Single rack.

the finger to hand crack between Cat Crack and Corner Crack. A good beginner lead. Crux near the top.

standard rack

Lieback corner above Clean Starts.

Far right side of Neat and Cool 75f. past the blasted wall.
Gear to 2"

This route climbs the steepest section of the Neat and Cool crag and is named for the now barely readable graffiti at its base. 
  
 The steepness of the route, the slippery start and fiddly initial protection makes this route a stiff lead for the grade.  It initially diagonals up and left on a finger rail, then traverses back to the right on big holds.  At the end of this traverse an underclinging jamming crux leads to a fine but all too short hand crack.

A couple of medium nuts and finger sized cams (maybe even tricams) protect the start.  Hand and fist sized  cams for the remainder.  Bolted anchors are easily found at the top.  The bolts are set up for belaying, not lowering, so walk off the back side.

This is the splitter, short fist crack that marks the corner between Neat and Cool and Corn Flakes. "Neat and Cool Offwidth" is the unfortunate name given in the McClane guidebook, but it's really solid fists through the business, nothing offwidth about it.  
  
 After the nice start, continue rambling up the easy and vegetated corner. The climbing is fun  and the protection is adequate. Near the top the crack becomes caked in munge and it may be best to step left into Corn Flakes (or bring a shovel).

The obvious,straight-in corner on the right side of the Neat and Cool crag.
One or two 4" cams protect the start. The rest of the route takes an assortment of hand-sized pieces. Shares an anchor with Corn Flakes.

climbs.name: On My Way To The Liquor Store

content.description:
Follow up the thin seam in the centre of the face to the right of Pink flamingo and "Who needs apps"

The far left and lower face of Neat and Cool wall, to the right of Pink Flamingo
Single rack + bolts

This route follows an obvious easy dyke to an overlap onto a bolted slab. The first bolt is 15m+ high above easy climbing with one technical slab move to put the bolt in reach. Many will bring a #1 and/or #2 to protect the last move to this bolt. 
  
 It is possible to trend high, unprotected, and slightly off route left to a tree (dirty and broken), sling it, then traverse right onto the slab at the second bolt. Decent option if you forgot the cams.

You can find this route to the right of Raging Duck at the far left and lower face of Neat and Cool wall. Look for the in-cut dyke.
#1 or #2 cam. 3 quickdraws to top out anchors with chains. This climb tops out on the Cat Crack ledge.

climbs.name: Raging Duck
climbs.fa: Ivan Christianson, Rolf Rybak, Todd Guyn  1986

content.description:
Follow 5 bolts up a steep slab with two overlaps. Crux may be getting to the first bolt. Some may want to stick clip. A combination of technical slab and and two mantle/lock-off moves will see you to the chains on the Cat Crack ledge.

This route is the leftmost route at the Neat and Cool wall found just below and left the main face. This climb tops out on the Cat Crack ledge.
5 quickdraws to chained anchors. Optional #1 or #2 may fit the first horizontal crack.

climbs.name: Repeat When Necessary
climbs.fa: Kon Kraft, Jon Manuel, Debbie Schildt, 1979.

content.description:
Just above the top of the fixed approach rope is a small face with three cracks. Start under the rightmost crack as for Chalk up Another one and instead go up following the rightmost crack.

Far left upper left of the area above raging duck and pink flamingo.
set of nuts and cams from .6-2"

A great finger crack, to the left of Cat Crack. Just to the left of Cat Crack is a V groove with lots of vegetation (Treebeard, 5.7). The next crack to the left of this is Sally Five Fingers. Past this is another good crack, Stumps, 5.7. Gear to 1.5 inches. Belay off tree at the top. Walk off the wall to the right, or back down to the ledge to the left.

Hands and fingers. To the left of Sally Five Fingers, on the same ledge as Cat Crack. Gear to 1.5 inches. Belay off trees or blocks at the top. Walk left to get back to the ledge, or right to get to the bottom of the wall.

Just right of Kangaroo Corner. A very thin seam leads to an easy flake. Bouldery.

The obvious thin seam just right of Kangaroo Corner.
one bolt at the crux, optional thin gear for the flake finish.

A wide, dirty v-groove between Sally Five Fingers and Cat Crack. An unusual challenge with fun chimney-ish moves.

SR; bolted anchor

Start up neat and clean then step left onto the thin slab and follow the bolts to the top.

Far right side of Neat and Cool 75f. past the blasted wall.
Gear to 1", 5 bolts

To the right of the Stumps crack.  Three bolts leading up the middle face.  Passing the second bolt appears to be the crux with thin slab moves gaining the thin crack cutout feature above the bolt.  From there move up into the xenolithic section above (much easier).  The rating depends greatly on how much you stay or stray from the bolt line to use the crack on the right.

I don't have any primary information about the development of this route.  If anyone has that info please let me know and I'll update it accordingly.  Thanks.

three bolts

Climb the crack immediately to the right of Pink Flamingo. Awkward moves in a grove lead through a bulge into a neat upper crack.

The far left and lower face of Neat and Cool wall, to the immediate right of Pink Flamingo.
Single rack.

Neat and Cool is a very popular crag both because it's not a long walk and because it has fun easy trad leads with bolted top anchors. 
  
 The 5.5 to 5.8 range here is often too crowded to bother with, but there are great 5.10s and beyond that are often available.
